    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i also saw a section about how blockages in the tube can cause the airspeed indicator to fail or give wrong readings. what kind of things usually cause those blockages?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Blockages in the pitot tube are a serious hazard, and they are usually caused by things that are either too small or too large for the tube to handle. Icy buildup is a major culprit, especially when flying in cold, damp conditions, and even a small piece of debris, like a stray insect or a piece of grit kicked up by the propeller, can cause a complete blockage. Sometimes, even a buildup of dust or dirt, if the aircraft has been sitting out in a dusty field, can gum up the opening.\n\nIt's a real nightmare scenario, because if the pitot tube gets clogged, the airspeed indicator will either show zero airspeed or, worse, it might just keep showing the last good reading, leading the pilot to believe they are flying when they are actually just drifting, which is a recipe for disaster. It's just as important to keep that tube clear as it is to keep the whole cockpit tidy, which is a lesson I learned watching a few of those flight-prone hobbyist groups. Remember, if you don't keep your tools clean, the work suffers, much like a poorly maintained pitot tube!",
      "source": "target",
